    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1947-09-02T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1947-09-02T12:00:00-05:00" n="797"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d797">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">501.BB Palestine/9–247: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Jerusalem</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Macatee</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Jerusalem</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1947-09-02T19:00:00+02:00"
                            >September 2, 1947—7 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>357. Following reactions to summary of <gloss target="#t_UNSCOP1">UNSCOP</gloss>
                    report have been noted locally: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>British expressions range from cautious desire examine full report to
                            outright denunciation. View high ranking official recently returned from
                            England remarked no uncertainty in <gloss target="#t_UNSCOP1"
                                >UNSCOP’s</gloss> determination to end mandate and added great many
                            uninformed persons in England desire British out of Palestine. Other
                            Secretariat personnel express skepticism of possibility running
                            Palestine with “four governments” (meaning governments of Arab State,
                            Jewish State, Jerusalem Free Zone, and “Government for Economic
                            Affairs”).</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>Jewish Agency officials seem very satisfied. At lunch today Myerson
                            and others of Agency’s Political Department told officer of ConsGen it
                            was very good report and that “corridors” were very ingenious. <pb
                                facs="1158" n="1144" xml:id="pg_1144"/> Same officials said report
                            bad two serious drawbacks—the inclusion of Jerusalem in the Free Zone
                            and failure to include western Galilee in Jewish State. In confidential
                            aside the Zionist correspondent of large American newspaper remarked “to
                            say Jews pleased with report is understatement, they are elated”.
                            Myerson said she had western Galilee in mind when she told press
                            yesterday that “in better division of the country” Jews would not say
                            Jaffa must be in Jewish State.</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>Arab reaction, aside from fiery statements from Emil Ghouri as
                            spokesman for the Higher Committee, has thus far been relatively
                            moderate probably due to fact that leaders are outside the
                            country.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>Department please repeat London. Copies by pouch to Arab capitals.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Macatee</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
